Publication Readiness Reference
Use this reference for final reviews before an article is published.
SEO Review
Check:
Primary search intent is satisfied in the first screen.
H1 matches the article promise.
H2s are descriptive and scannable.
The article answers common reader questions directly.
Title is compelling without exaggerated health promises.
Meta description is clear, specific, and under about 155 characters when possible.
FAQ questions match real reader concerns and avoid unsafe medical promises.
Internal links are relevant and naturally placed.
Image alt text describes the image and supports accessibility.
Editorial Review
Check:
Plain-language explanations are accurate and not patronizing.
Practical tips are realistic and low friction.
The article distinguishes evidence, expert consensus, and personal preference.
There is no shame-based or fear-based framing.
The draft avoids needless jargon.
The conclusion gives a useful next step.
Safety Review
Check:
No diagnosis, prescription, treatment plan, cure, or guaranteed outcome.
Risky tips include contraindications or professional-care guidance.
Supplement and product claims are limited and source-backed.
Urgent symptoms direct readers toward urgent or emergency care.
Disclaimer is visible and appropriate to the topic.
Medical review is recommended for medium- or high-risk topics.
Publication Checklist
Return one of these recommendations:
Ready: no material safety, evidence, or SEO gaps.
Ready after edits: small wording, citation, or structure issues remain.
Needs expert review: clinical, regulatory, or safety-sensitive claims remain.
Not ready: unsupported or unsafe claims could mislead readers.
